INDEX BIBLICVS: OR AN EXACT CONCORDANCE TO THE HOLY BIBLE, According to the
last Translation.

Whereunto are added The Marginal Readings, with the Acceptations and various
Significations of the Principal Words contained in the HOLY SCRIPTURES of the
OLD and NEW TESTAMENTS.

Composed in a New and most Comprehensive Method, and Adorned with diverse
Significant and Pregnant Scripture-Phrases.

By JOHN JACKSON, Minister of the Gospel at Moulsea in Surrey.

(...).

Nonn. Paraph. in Joh. 5.39. (...),

1 Timothy 4.13. ALMA MATTER CANTABRIGIA
HINC LVCEM ET POCVLA SACRA printer's or publisher's device

CAMBRIDGE: Printed by JOHN FIELD, Printer to the University, 1668.

Directions for the diligent Scripture-Reader.
FOr the better directions of those, into whose hands this Work shall come, and
the method in which it is composed; be pleased to observe these things.

I. The design of it is all along to keep close to Bible-order, which is
generally observed; albeit you must know, that always where diverse Texts do
contain in them one and the same Word or Sentence, such Texts are ranged
together, as standing in a body represented at one view, making some alteration
of the order, ex gr. under the Title Word Abundance. a. of sea, Deuteronomy. 33.19.
Isa 60.5. where, because a. of sea is found in that Text of Isaiah, as well as
in Deuteronomy, they stand together, though before 1 Samuel 1.16. which
otherwise, to have kept exactly to Bible-order, should have been repeated after
a. of thy enchantments.

II. There are several parallel Texts not mentioned, being parallel, and
already quoted; besides for the most part in Quarto Bibles and Octavo, as also
some Twelves they will be found in the Marginal References.

III. Some Title-Words have nothing but Quotations under them, either because
they are but few, and seldom found in Scripture, and therefore quickly perused,
as in Abundant, Absent, Acceptance, Access, etc. or if often, they are not of
frequent use, or may be better found under more material words then the Title
or Simple Theme is; and this happens most commonly, though not always in
Undeclined Parts of Speech, as Above, Abundantly, etc.

IV. If you miss of any material Text among the Words and Sentences where
properly you might have expected it, you will find it either among the Various
Acceptations, or standing immediately under the Title-Word; if in neither, you
are but where the most complete and largest Concordance does sometimes leave
you, viz. to search for it under some other word, so will thou as rarely miss
of any Text desired, as in any Concordance whatever.

V. You may possibly (though seldom) miss a Text or two under some Derivative
word, as in Participles, and in Second or Third Persons of Verbs, etc. which
ordinarily may be found among the Various Acceptations of the Simple Theme, ex
gr. in Raises you miss Psalm. 113.7. r. out the poor out of the dust, and Psalm.
107.25. r. the stormy wind; both which Texts you will find in the Various
Acceptations under Raised: So in Redeeming you will miss Ephesians. 5.16. r. the
time, which you will find in the Various Acceptations under Redeemed, and thus
frequently in many others; sometimes also the Verb in the Substantive, and
contra, as in Will Verb, and Wills you will miss Phil. 2.13. both to w. and
to do, and Romans 9.16. not of him that w. both which you will find in the
Various Acceptations in Will Substant, and in several others.

VI. You will very frequently find in the Sentences several Particles to be
understood, which, by them that know the use of Concordances, may readily be
supplied to make up the Sense, as a. the, this, that, etc. Persons and Signs of
Tenses, etc. which being repeated will commonly make the sense entire, or at
least intelligible.

VII. Where you find Figures without Scripture, you must refer it to the last
Scripture mentioned and where one single Figure, it is a Verse of the foregoing
Chapter.

If herein I have done any thing, that may contribute to the increase of your
knowledge in the Scriptures, I shall heartily rejoice, and in a short time
forget my long and tedious travail, for joy that the Work is brought forth to
the profiting of the Church; which is the hearty prayer of

Yours in any work of the Gospel, JOHN JACKSON.

Note, that
is for a Marginal Reading. * is for Synonymous terms or Phrases. is for
distinguishing of Chapters.. after a Figure notes a Chapters., after a Figure
notes the Verse.
